Here is a possible database schema for a messaging system with friends, attachments, individual chat, group chat, and an inbox: 
 
Users 
 
id (primary key): unique identifier for each user 
name: the user's name 
email: the user's email address 
password: hashed password for the user's account 
created_at: timestamp for when the user's account was created 
Friends 
 
id (primary key): unique identifier for each friendship 
user1_id (foreign key): the id of the first user in the friendship 
user2_id (foreign key): the id of the second user in the friendship 
status: the status of the friendship (pending, accepted, or blocked) 
created_at: timestamp for when the friendship was created 
Messages 
 
id (primary key): unique identifier for each message 
sender_id (foreign key): the id of the user who sent the message 
recipient_id (foreign key): the id of the user who received the message 
group_id (foreign key): the id of the group the message was sent to (null if the message was sent to an individual) 
body: the content of the message 
created_at: timestamp for when the message was sent 
Groups 
 
id (primary key): unique identifier for each group 
name: the name of the group 
created_at: timestamp for when the group was created 
Group Members 
 
id (primary key): unique identifier for each group membership 
group_id (foreign key): the id of the group the user is a member of 
user_id (foreign key): the id of the user who is a member of the group 
Attachments 
 
id (primary key): unique identifier for each attachment 
message_id (foreign key): the id of the message the attachment was sent with 
file_name: the name of the attachment file 
file_type: the type of the attachment file (e.g. image, video, etc.) 
file_size: the size of the attachment file 
Inbox 
 
id (primary key): unique identifier for each inbox entry 
message_id (foreign key): the id of the message in the inbox 
user_id (foreign key): the id of the user who the inbox belongs to 
is_read: a boolean indicating whether the message has been read by the user 
This is just one possible way to design a database schema for a messaging system, and there may be other ways to organize the data depending on the specific requirements of the application.
